
[1]saddle

   SADDLE, n. sad'l. [L. sedeo, sedile.]

   1. A seat to be placed on a horse's back for the rider to sit on.
   Saddles are variously made, as the common saddle and the hunting
   saddle, and for females the side-saddle.

   2. Among seamen, a cleat or block of wood nailed on the lower yard-arms
   to retain the studding sail-booms in their place. The name is given
   also to other circular pieces of wood; as the saddle of the bow-spirit.
